**Abstract:**
Major essay titled "Practical Understanding" continuing 98-APR-1. Extensive analysis of Aristotle-Aquinas on speculative vs. practical knowledge from Metaphysics Lectio 1. Argues there is no speculative knowledge--all knowledge is prospective and practical. Develops distinction between animal experimentum and human linguistic knowledge. Critiques Nussbaum on "practical necessity" and akratia. Discusses prudentia, deliberation, and the contingency of all action.

**AI Recommendation:** Major theoretical essay; see 98-APR-2-1 variant. Central to practical knowledge thesis.

